  "text": "The alerting logic of ALAS considered in this paper issues an alert when the aircraft are predicted to violate some distance thresholds called Front and Back [CITATION_1] . To predict this violation, the aircraft projects the current state of the system with three different dynamics: first, the intruder does not turn, i.e., banking angle 0 • , second, the intruder turns with the specified bank angle φ i and third, the intruder turns with the maximum bank angle φ max . If any of these projections violates the distance thresholds, then an alert is issued. The alert predicates for the each one of these projections are represented by Alert 0 , Alert φi and Alert φmax , respectively. Thus, the alerting logic considered in this paper is defined as Alert ≡ Alert 0 ∨ Alert φi ∨ Alert φmax .",
